Today’s class focused on the fundamentals of HTML and how web pages are structured. HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is used 
to create and design web pages. The mentor explained that an HTML document follows a standard structure, which includes 
elements like <html>, <head>, and <body>. The <head> section contains metadata such as the title of the page, while the 
<body> section contains the actual content that is displayed in the browser.

The session introduced basic HTML tags used to structure content. Heading tags (<h1> to <h6>) are used to display titles, 
    paragraph tags (<p>) are used to write text content, anchor tags (<a>) are used to create links between pages, and image 
        tags (<img>) are used to display images. Each tag has a specific purpose and helps in organizing the content clearly.

The mentor explained how browsers read HTML code line by line and render it visually on the screen. Proper use of tags ensures 
that the content is displayed correctly. Attributes such as href in anchor tags and src in image tags are used to provide 
additional information to elements.

The working flow starts with writing HTML code in a file and saving it with a .html extension. When the file is opened in a 
browser, the browser interprets the tags and displays the content accordingly. This helps in creating structured and 
user-friendly web pages.

Understanding HTML is important because it forms the foundation of web development.